00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:00.100
GILBERT: Coney Island
is an amusement park.

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:01.430
Imagine that.

00:03:01.430 --> 00:03:04.500
An entire park dedicated to
nothing more than a feeling.

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:10.460
And theres a whole lot of
feeling going on around here.

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:13.660
"People are happy and relaxed,"

00:03:13.660 --> 00:03:16.400
"excited and frightened,"

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:19.360
"exhausted and relieved,"

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:22.700
"and yes, sometimes
even amused."

00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:24.700
"Human emotions are
a rollercoaster,"

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:31.130
taking each of us from delight
to despair and back again.

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:36.860
We like the ups much
more than the downs.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:41.230
"But the fact is that emotions
like anger, fear and sadness"

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:44.860
have a critical role
to play in our lives.

00:03:44.860 --> 00:03:47.200
Negative emotions are
both our best friend

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:49.960
"and our worst enemy, and
science is beginning"

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:55.260
to help us understand how
that paradox is possible.

00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:58.800
McENROE: In the 80s
there was a poll done in
one of the newspapers.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:00.660
"The most heinous, you know,"

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:03.530
"people in the 20th
century, you know."

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:07.200
It was like Jack the
Ripper was one...

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:09.260
"I was two, Charles
Manson was three."

00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:11.030
"You know, I mean it was like,"

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:13.430
"""Wait a second, okay, I
yelled at an umpire, okay?"

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:16.860
"I didnt mutilate 40
people or whatever."""

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:18.600
ALANIS MORISSETTE:
Anger feels hot.

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:23.260
"Even talking about anger,
my whole rib cage is warm."

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:24.930
My legs are mobilized.

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:26.430
Its the fight.

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:28.160
I feel my jaw getting clenched.

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:30.160
I want to punch something.

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:33.130
"You know, I-I used to be the
kind of guy who, I would,"

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:35.030
I would scream on the street.

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:37.700
I was screaming
on street corners.

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:43.160
"When, when I asked somebody the
time and they go, (mutters)"

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:52.960
"You know, I would scream,
Id get in fights, you know?"

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:54.660
MARY MOLINA: I was in a bar.

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:57.730
And I was with my girlfriend.

00:04:57.730 --> 00:05:00.930
"Across the way, there
were three huge dudes"

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:06.000
and they were there chilling
and sort of saying things

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.600
amongst themselves about her.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:13.860
"And um, so, you know, that
really got to me to the point"

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:18.360
"where I got up off my chair
and I walked over to them,"

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:21.900
"and then in a sort of
methodical sort of way,"

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:23.760
"you know, sort of
start picking at them."

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:29.130
"""Youre a fat piece of lardass,
you rich (bleep) mamas boy."

00:05:29.130 --> 00:05:31.130
"Youre being a real (bleeps)."""

00:05:31.130 --> 00:05:38.100
Do you understand that?

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.600
"When I want to hurt somebody,"

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:43.330
Im not thinking about
how could they hurt me.

00:05:43.330 --> 00:05:46.700
Im thinking about
how angry I am.

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:52.330
It just... it just drives you.

00:05:52.330 --> 00:05:55.430
GILBERT: Mary is
a Los Angeles-based
writer and filmmaker

00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:59.030
who knows what its like to
be in the grip of anger.

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:00.630
Para que es esto?

00:06:00.630 --> 00:06:03.130
"I was born in
Barenquia, Colombia,"

00:06:03.130 --> 00:06:06.230
which is on the northern
coast of South America.

00:06:06.230 --> 00:06:11.200
My family moved here
when I was ten years old.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:14.800
My father was very frustrated.

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:18.460
He would do things
like punch walls

00:06:18.460 --> 00:06:22.360
and kick doors down
and things like that.

00:06:22.360 --> 00:06:24.200
He was really tense.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:25.930
He was really angry.

00:06:25.930 --> 00:06:28.930
"By the time that
I was like 14, 15,"

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:31.660
I was really reacting.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:35.500
I was so angry at him
that I wanted to...

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:38.760
"uh... I almost kind of
wanted to fight him,"

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:41.100
to see who would win.

00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:43.700
"Eventually it sort
of progressed, uh,"

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:46.230
"just sort of like a general
anger towards people,"

00:06:46.230 --> 00:06:48.700
"towards things, towards, uh,"

00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:58.230
a world that didnt
understand me.

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:00.530
"MAN: You could follow
through a little more, too."

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:02.200
On the right or on
the left or on both?

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:03.600
Yeah. On the right. On
the right. On the right?

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:05.100
"Yeah, especially. Okay."

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:08.560
"When I get into arguments,
get into fights,"

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:11.830
I only see that person

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:17.760
or that thing in front of
me that I want to attack.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:20.130
"And then Im acutely
assessing the situation,"

00:07:20.130 --> 00:07:25.060
"but only for one purpose,
and thats to win."

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:28.230
GILBERT: When animals are
threatened they experience
a surge of hormones

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:31.100
that make them ready to
attack or to retreat.

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:34.100
Human animals are no exception.

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:38.260
Our fight-or-flight response
is crucial for our survival.

00:07:38.260 --> 00:07:40.500
ROBERT ALLAN: Anger
can feel exhilarating

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:46.600
because what we do is trigger
the fight-or-flight response.

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:50.430
We secrete lots of adrenaline
to power our large muscles

00:07:50.430 --> 00:07:53.760
in the event that we have to
fight or flee from the predator.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:55.760
"We secrete cortisol,"

00:07:55.760 --> 00:07:58.100
which heightens our auditory
and visual sensitivities.

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:00.160
"We stop digesting lunch,"

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:01.830
because who needs
to digest lunch

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:05.800
if youre about to become lunch?

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:09.230
"Now, that response
is very appropriate"

00:08:09.230 --> 00:08:12.730
when were dealing with
life-threatening danger.

00:08:12.730 --> 00:08:16.560
"However, the Yellow Cab driver
that cut you off in traffic"

00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:19.560
comes to supplant the
saber-toothed tiger

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:25.500
"that our ancestors, millennia
ago, were dealing with."

00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:28.300
"And when we look at what
happens physiologically,"

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:33.330
we stay in this heightened state
for quite some period of time.

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:36.930
"And, because were dealing
with fight or flight,"

00:08:36.930 --> 00:08:41.130
were dealing with impulses
that are very strong.

00:08:41.130 --> 00:08:44.300
(people cheering)

00:08:44.300 --> 00:08:46.660
"(cheering, applause)"

00:08:46.660 --> 00:08:49.400
"GILBERT: The
emotions associated
with fight or flight,"

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:51.400
"emotions like anger and fear,"

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:53.130
are triggered deep
inside our brain.

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:57.530
"MAN: Five, four,
three, two, one, tug."

00:08:57.530 --> 00:09:01.130
"GILBERT: And when we
try to control them,
we start a tug-of-war"

00:09:01.130 --> 00:09:03.130
between our brains
oldest and newest parts.

00:09:03.130 --> 00:09:04.730
"(cheering, applause)"

00:09:04.730 --> 00:09:08.560
While ancient structures
like the amygdala

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:12.560
"respond to threats by trying
to turn our anger or fear on,"

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:16.060
"its newer structures, such
as the prefrontal cortex--"

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:19.530
the thinking part of our brain--
that try to turn them off.

00:09:19.530 --> 00:09:21.560
Its the tug-of-war

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:24.160
between these two systems that
gives rise to our emotions.

00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:25.830
"At New York University,"

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:29.500
neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux
has studied how the amygdala

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:33.000
and the cortex shape our
emotional responses.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
"You know more about the
amygdala than anybody alive,"

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:36.560
and you still cant
control yours.

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:37.930
No. Why?

00:09:37.930 --> 00:09:39.930
"Now, theres an
interesting thing again"

00:09:39.930 --> 00:09:42.030
that has to do with the
wiring of the brain.

00:09:42.030 --> 00:09:44.660
"So, if we could
look at it here..."

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:47.700
"So, this is the human brain,"

00:09:47.700 --> 00:09:49.700
"inside a skull,"

00:09:49.700 --> 00:09:52.030
"and the prefrontal cortex
is here in the front,"

00:09:52.030 --> 00:09:54.060
right behind your forehead.

00:09:54.060 --> 00:09:57.230
And that is the newest
part of the brain.

00:09:57.230 --> 00:09:59.230
"This is where we
make our decisions,"

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:00.930
"this is where we
plan for the future,"

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:03.430
"um, and strategize."

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:06.330
The lateral prefrontal
cortex has no connectivity

00:10:06.330 --> 00:10:07.700
with the amygdala.

00:10:07.700 --> 00:10:10.700
The amygdala has super highways
to talk to the cortex.

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:14.060
But the prefrontal cortex
has only back roads

00:10:14.060 --> 00:10:16.100
and side streets to
get to the amygdala.

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:18.900
"And therefore, it is unable
to tell the amygdala,"

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:20.130
"""Cool it."""

00:10:20.130 --> 00:10:22.230
But why are there
no connections?

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:24.560
"Were in the process of
evolving as we speak,"

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:27.400
and those connections
have not been put in yet.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:29.400
This thing was built

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:31.400
"to do fancy things
cognitively,"

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:33.360
not necessarily to
control our emotions.

00:10:33.360 --> 00:10:38.260
(thunder rumbling)

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:40.760
GILBERT: The fact that
we are not designed

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:42.760
to have complete control
over our emotions

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:46.830
can have some unfortunate
consequences.

00:10:46.830 --> 00:10:49.860
"MOLINA: I was in such
a deep, dark place"

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:53.730
that I couldnt even
really see myself.

00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:56.730
"Like, I had become
this, like..."

00:10:56.730 --> 00:11:02.400
muddled thing of a person.

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:04.830
I was so sad.

00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:06.830
I was so angry.

00:11:06.830 --> 00:11:10.330
I couldnt get beyond it.

00:11:10.330 --> 00:11:13.000
I realized I had to do something

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.100
when I hit rock bottom.

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:22.500
(indistinct chattering)

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:26.260
One of my friends
invited me to a party.

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:28.600
"And I was having a great time,"

00:11:28.600 --> 00:11:31.100
"but, uh, because
Im a control freak,"

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:33.460
I decided that I wanted
to change the song.

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:38.260
I wanted to go over to the
iPod and change the song.

00:11:38.260 --> 00:11:41.530
"So, the guy whose party it was"

00:11:41.530 --> 00:11:44.200
"came over to me, and hes
like, ""What are you doing?"""

00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:48.500
And I... boom.

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:51.430
"I just went off. Im like, ""Who
are you?"" And he was like,"

00:11:51.430 --> 00:11:54.000
"""Its my party, and Im
gonna play what I want."""

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.260
"Im like, ""Youre a (bleep)
selfish (bleep)."""

00:11:57.260 --> 00:11:58.930
"And I just slapped
him across the face,"

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:03.000
and his glasses went
flying across the room.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:07.660
"Um, and so, at that moment,"

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:11.130
it was like everything
sort of fell away.

00:12:11.130 --> 00:12:12.330
You know what I mean?

00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:14.330
"Like, there were at
least another 20,"

00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:17.500
"30 people in the room, and
I could see none of them."

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:19.500
"They just turned
into like this blur,"

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:22.130
and all I could
see was this guy.

00:12:22.130 --> 00:12:26.430
"He grabbed a chunk of my hair,"

00:12:26.430 --> 00:12:29.160
"and he hung onto
it really tight,"

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:30.400
so I just started kicking him.

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:32.300
"I was just, like,
laying on him."

00:12:32.300 --> 00:12:34.160
"I was like, ""Let
go, let go, let go."""

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:35.760
"I kept on saying,
""Let go, let go."""

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:37.530
I just kept on kicking him.

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:39.860
"Just kicking him and kicking
him and kicking him,"

00:12:39.860 --> 00:12:43.030
"um, until he finally let go."

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:48.460
And at that point...

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:52.030
(sighs)

00:12:52.030 --> 00:12:57.760
I just started crying.

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:01.530
You know?

00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:06.360
"And, uh, it was like
everything became real again."

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:10.400
"And all the people,"

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:13.900
"um, were there, and
they were looking at me"

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:16.830
"with such, like,
shock and awe."

00:13:16.830 --> 00:13:19.700
And I...

00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:23.560
I felt horrible...

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:28.560
...that I... that I did it.

00:13:28.560 --> 00:13:30.530
Thats what hurts me.

00:13:30.530 --> 00:13:32.130
"And that I shouldnt, you know?"

00:13:32.130 --> 00:13:33.630
That it goes against my values.

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:37.000
"It goes against
who I am, you know?"

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:38.430
Um...

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:48.800
Thats... thats...
thats what hurts me.

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:51.530
ALLAN: Think about what
happens after an argument

00:13:51.530 --> 00:13:53.600
that was really intense.

00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:55.200
People feel terrible.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:57.630
"Oftentimes, they feel
depressed afterwards."

00:13:57.630 --> 00:14:01.030
Its not a good
long-term solution.

00:14:01.030 --> 00:14:03.630
"ADAM GOPNIK: Anger, uh...
its not a helpful emotion."

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.760
Its not always an
appropriate emotion.

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:08.130
"And, in the cases
in my own life"

00:14:08.130 --> 00:14:10.630
when Ive allowed it free range--

00:14:10.630 --> 00:14:12.260
Ive allowed it action--

00:14:12.260 --> 00:14:13.900
Ive always regretted it after.

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:16.260
I dont... I cant think of a time

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:18.830
when Ive seen my own anger

00:14:18.830 --> 00:14:21.900
as something that was
constructive for me

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:24.430
"or, uh, useful in the world."

00:14:24.430 --> 00:14:26.360
But Ive noticed where
my anger comes out

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:28.900
in subtle or not so
subtle ways and how its...

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:32.630
"its wrought a lot of havoc in
my personal life, so, um..."

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:36.200
including the... the anger
that Ive turned toward me.

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:37.530
McENROE: Have I lost it

00:14:37.530 --> 00:14:39.200
to the point where I did feel

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:40.560
like Ive lost it? Yeah.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:42.900
Its not easy to feel
like you made an ass

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:46.130
"out of yourself, perhaps,
and get through that."

00:14:46.130 --> 00:14:47.430
But people do...

00:14:47.430 --> 00:14:56.860
I think people make mistakes
every day of their life.

00:14:56.860 --> 00:15:01.430
GILBERT: Can we
outsmart our own brains?

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:05.600
Can we learn to
control our emotions?

00:15:05.600 --> 00:15:07.960
Stanford psychologist
James Gross

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:09.660
has spent his career studying

00:15:09.660 --> 00:15:12.600
"what scientists call
""emotion regulation."""

00:15:12.600 --> 00:15:14.530
"GROSS: For me,
emotion regulation"

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:17.030
is really the science
of understanding

00:15:17.030 --> 00:15:19.500
"how we can modify
our emotions,"

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:23.200
"harness their energy, so
that we can direct them"

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:25.560
in ways that we wish to go.

00:15:25.560 --> 00:15:27.800
"So, for me, emotion regulation"

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:30.260
"isnt turning down or
turning off all emotions,"

00:15:30.260 --> 00:15:33.160
"because emotions, I think,
are often incredibly helpful"

00:15:33.160 --> 00:15:35.500
and are what make us who we are.

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.130
"But I think, at times,
its great to have"

00:15:38.130 --> 00:15:41.100
a set of tools that we
can avail ourselves of

00:15:41.100 --> 00:15:43.160
so that we can change the course

00:15:43.160 --> 00:15:46.530
of the emotions
that were having.

00:15:46.530 --> 00:15:50.460
"GILBERT: To test his theory,
Gross asked about 100 women"

00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:52.500
to take part in an experiment.

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:55.500
Each woman was wired
up to a machine

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:58.800
"so that researchers could
measure her heart rate,"

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:01.660
pulse and perspiration--

00:16:01.660 --> 00:16:08.960
all physiological indicators
of emotional arousal.

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:11.200
"First, the women
were asked to recall"

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:14.230
a recent incident that
had made them angry

00:16:14.230 --> 00:16:17.760
"and to think about the
incident again and again,"

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:20.130
"to keep turning it
over in their minds,"

00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:24.930
to consider and
reconsider every detail.

00:16:24.930 --> 00:16:29.200
"Scientists call this
""rumination."""

00:16:29.200 --> 00:16:32.660
"To Mary, this way of thinking
came quite naturally."

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:34.130
MOLINA: I didnt understand

00:16:34.130 --> 00:16:37.860
"why it was so easy for
me to, like, just..."

00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:40.400
go into these ranting raves

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:42.900
"and just become so obsessed
on this thing, okay."

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:44.300
"""You... you
forgot to call me."

00:16:44.300 --> 00:16:45.730
"""Why did you
forget to call me?"

00:16:45.730 --> 00:16:46.730
"""You shouldve called me."

00:16:46.730 --> 00:16:47.900
"""I dont understand."

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:49.760
"""Okay, you were busy,
but I re... I re..."

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:51.200
"I reminded you
several times."""

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:54.160
"You become fixated on these
things, you know, like..."

00:16:54.160 --> 00:16:59.060
and you dont take a
moment to breathe.

00:16:59.060 --> 00:17:01.500
"GILBERT: In the next
phase of the experiment,"

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:03.400
the women were
again asked to think

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:05.860
"about the incident
that made them angry,"

00:17:05.860 --> 00:17:08.600
but this time to
try to visualize it

00:17:08.600 --> 00:17:10.260
as a neutral observer

00:17:10.260 --> 00:17:12.300
or from the perspective
of the other person.

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:18.000
"This is a technique
that scientists call
""reappraisal."""

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:19.600
"When the subjects ruminated,"

00:17:19.600 --> 00:17:22.960
their cardiovascular
system went into overdrive.

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:25.330
"When they reappraised,"

00:17:25.330 --> 00:17:28.560
"their bodies became calmer,
and their anger diminished."

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:32.100
One of the things that
people for a very long time

00:17:32.100 --> 00:17:35.460
"have, uh, repeated
again and again is that,"

00:17:35.460 --> 00:17:37.130
"actually, theres
an important role"

00:17:37.130 --> 00:17:39.630
"for thinking in
emotions, and if you can"

00:17:39.630 --> 00:17:44.500
"change the way you think, you
can change the way you feel."

00:17:44.500 --> 00:17:47.360
GILBERT: Marys introduction
to emotion regulation

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:49.630
came through a therapist

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:52.830
who helped her explore
the roots of her anger

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:55.830
and suggested ways she
could better control it.

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:59.130
MOLINA: One of the things that
I have sort of grown to accept

00:17:59.130 --> 00:18:00.500
"in the last couple of years,"

00:18:00.500 --> 00:18:02.130
"especially going
through therapy,"

00:18:02.130 --> 00:18:06.160
"is that I have to stop myself
and just take a breath,"

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:11.100
and then also think about the...
the person in front of me.

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:14.600
"To, like, really see them as
someone who makes mistakes,"

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:16.530
and maybe didnt
say what they mean

00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:19.730
or maybe had a rough
day at work today.

00:18:19.730 --> 00:18:21.460
"Youre in the middle
of an argument,"

00:18:21.460 --> 00:18:24.400
"and youre so riled
up, and youre so ready"

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:27.630
to fight for something
incredibly stupid.

00:18:27.630 --> 00:18:30.060
"Uh, that feels,
like, primordial."

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:32.830
Its hard to think about
the people around you

00:18:32.830 --> 00:18:34.930
and how its
affecting them. Um...

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:37.000
Have you tried to put any
of this into practice--

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.230
"like, taking it out for a
test drive, this advice?"

00:18:39.230 --> 00:18:41.130
Yeah. Yeah. And...?

00:18:41.130 --> 00:18:42.660
Did it work?

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:44.460
"Its hard, hard work,"

00:18:44.460 --> 00:18:45.660
but it works.

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:46.860
You practice.

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:48.230
"You know, its like anything."

00:18:48.230 --> 00:18:49.660
"Its like learning an
instrument-- you practice,"

00:18:49.660 --> 00:18:53.600
"and you learn some basic
tools, and you always go back"

00:18:53.600 --> 00:18:58.430
to those tools when
all things fail.

00:18:58.430 --> 00:19:00.960
"Back in the day, you know,
I had to go to therapy,"

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:03.230
"and I found it... it
saved me cause I was very,"

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:04.630
"you know, kind of
self-destructive."

00:19:04.630 --> 00:19:06.060
I was always acting out.

00:19:06.060 --> 00:19:09.960
Four years of that twice a
week made a huge difference.

00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:11.700
ELIZABETH GILBERT:
Its a wonderful thing

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:14.530
to... to be able to go
to somebody who you...

00:19:14.530 --> 00:19:16.960
"who didnt raise you, who
youre not married to,"

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:19.660
"who you dont have a 15-year
friendship relationship with,"

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:21.130
and... and be able to tell them

00:19:21.130 --> 00:19:24.060
what you secretly are
longing for and needing

00:19:24.060 --> 00:19:25.700
without feeling that
youre going to be judged

00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:26.930
"or, um... or that youre going"

00:19:26.930 --> 00:19:28.760
to hurt their feelings
if this comes out.

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:32.800
"So, by being able to unload
these feelings to this doctor--"

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:37.000
"and I did, I told
her everything that was
making me feel crummy,"

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:38.960
"uh, and we discussed it--"

00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:40.800
"when I walked out
of there, you know,"

00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:42.860
maybe between the
time I left her office

00:19:42.860 --> 00:19:47.330
"and into my car, I
was floating on air."

00:19:47.330 --> 00:19:51.760
GILBERT: Psychotherapy has been
with us for more than a century.

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:54.900
Sigmund Freud was the first to
suggest that emotional problems

00:19:54.900 --> 00:19:57.100
"may be the symptoms of
something much deeper,"

00:19:57.100 --> 00:19:58.360
"something more significant,"

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:01.130
"something the mind is
hiding from itself,"

00:20:01.130 --> 00:20:03.360
such as a traumatic
childhood experience

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:06.500
or a forbidden sexual impulse.

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:08.460
So he had people
lie on his couch

00:20:08.460 --> 00:20:11.030
and talk about their
dreams and their childhood

00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:13.300
in the hope that they
might say something

00:20:13.300 --> 00:20:17.230
that would reveal the true cause
of their emotional distress.

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:20.030
"This kind of therapy
was intense, complex,"

00:20:20.030 --> 00:20:21.960
and went on for
a very long time.

00:20:21.960 --> 00:20:23.360
"WOODY ALLEN: Uh,
yes, eight years,"

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:25.360
"I was on a couch, and, um,"

00:20:25.360 --> 00:20:28.160
"five years, I was allowed to
sit up and face him and..."

00:20:28.160 --> 00:20:29.800
"GILBERT: In a 1970s interview,"

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:31.560
comedian Woody Allen
poked fun at the process.

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:33.560
"I dont know. DICK CAVETT:
How do you know, really?"

00:20:33.560 --> 00:20:35.200
Thats what is always
the big question mark

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:38.330
"for me, is when do you
decide, ""Im done""?"

00:20:38.330 --> 00:20:39.600
"Ah, thats a good point."

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:41.360
I dont know if youre
ever really done.

00:20:41.360 --> 00:20:43.060
I know that certain
characteristics about me

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:45.360
are different now than they
were when I started analysis.

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:49.600
"Im... I started when I
was, uh, 22, and Im 35."

00:20:49.600 --> 00:20:51.600
"So, I have aged."

00:20:51.600 --> 00:20:53.360
"Thats something. (Cavett,
audience laughing)"

00:20:53.360 --> 00:20:55.830
"Uh... That is progress,
cause its upward."

00:20:55.830 --> 00:20:57.460
"Yes. Yes. Um, yeah."

00:20:57.460 --> 00:21:00.600
"Uh, and I can... when I have
sexual relations with someone,"

00:21:00.600 --> 00:21:03.660
I can now think of that person.

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:05.160
"Rather than...? Rather
than somebody else,"

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:07.560
which is an enormous
step forward to me.

00:21:07.560 --> 00:21:09.330
How many years did that take?

00:21:09.330 --> 00:21:10.730
"Where did that
come in, roughly?"

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:12.700
That just came in last week. Oh.

00:21:12.700 --> 00:21:15.860
"GILBERT: In recent years,
Freuds therapy has evolved"

00:21:15.860 --> 00:21:17.960
"into a more streamlined
form of the treatment,"

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:20.530
known as psychodynamic therapy.

00:21:20.530 --> 00:21:22.630
The television
series The Sopranos

00:21:22.630 --> 00:21:25.200
introduced the therapy
to a new generation.

00:21:25.200 --> 00:21:27.730
So youre carrying all this guilt

00:21:27.730 --> 00:21:31.160
when your mother is clearly
someone who has great difficulty

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:35.160
in maintaining a
relationship with anyone.

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:37.160
But shes my mother.

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:40.900
RICHARD FRIEDMAN:
Psychodynamic psychotherapy
focuses on the role

00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:43.130
of unconscious conflict

00:21:43.130 --> 00:21:46.460
"in causing your problems
in relationships,"

00:21:46.460 --> 00:21:49.100
"in your love life,
in your work life,"

00:21:49.100 --> 00:21:52.560
"so that these are things that
are largely hidden from you,"

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:54.360
but they are making
you miserable.

00:21:54.360 --> 00:21:56.460
And the role of
psychodynamic psychotherapy

00:21:56.460 --> 00:21:58.600
"is to uncover them, to
make them conscious,"

00:21:58.600 --> 00:22:00.230
to make you aware of that.

00:22:00.230 --> 00:22:03.200
The focus is on helping the
patient develop insight

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:07.360
into how things they feel today
or expectations they have

00:22:07.360 --> 00:22:11.160
"about life and about people
come from their past,"

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:14.260
and that the insight
itself helps them to...

00:22:14.260 --> 00:22:16.560
to change their behavior
and their ways of thinking

00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:18.000
and... and helps
with the symptoms

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.830
they might be experiencing.

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:24.400
GILBERT: Psychodynamic
therapy is based on the fact

00:22:24.400 --> 00:22:26.260
that people dont always know

00:22:26.260 --> 00:22:29.830
why they feel and think
and act as they do.

00:22:29.830 --> 00:22:31.330
"But in recent years,"

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:32.860
some psychologists
have suggested

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:34.330
that rather than searching

00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:36.660
"for the hidden causes
of emotional problems,"

00:22:36.660 --> 00:22:38.300
therapists might
just help people

00:22:38.300 --> 00:22:40.760
develop the skills they
need to deal with them.

00:22:40.760 --> 00:22:43.930
"This idea is the basis of a
different kind of therapy,"

00:22:43.930 --> 00:22:45.830
one thats helping
people learn to control

00:22:45.830 --> 00:22:58.960
one of the most primitive
human emotions: fear.

00:22:58.960 --> 00:23:02.060
Christina Kelley is a
freshman at Harvard.

00:23:02.060 --> 00:23:06.360
"Shes a great student
and a terrific athlete,"

00:23:06.360 --> 00:23:08.860
but shes deathly
afraid to do something

00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:11.300
that millions of
Americans find easy.

00:23:11.300 --> 00:23:13.560
KELLEY: I am afraid of flying.

00:23:13.560 --> 00:23:15.160
Its not rational-- I know that--

00:23:15.160 --> 00:23:16.730
"but at the same time,"

00:23:16.730 --> 00:23:18.360
thats definitely just
what makes it a phobia.

00:23:18.360 --> 00:23:20.230
"I just cant... I
know its irrational,"

00:23:20.230 --> 00:23:26.830
and I cant do anything about it.

00:23:26.830 --> 00:23:28.730
Its not that Im...

00:23:28.730 --> 00:23:30.800
afraid that theyre going to
go crashing to the ground

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:32.230
"or that someones
going to, you know,"

00:23:32.230 --> 00:23:33.760
"try to take it
over or anything,"

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:36.330
but... theres not
really anything

00:23:36.330 --> 00:23:38.760
"that I can, like, pinpoint
as to why Im afraid,"

00:23:38.760 --> 00:23:40.460
and so I think that kind of adds

00:23:40.460 --> 00:23:44.830
"to the whole, like,
overarching fear."

00:23:44.830 --> 00:23:48.160
GILBERT: Is fear of
flying really irrational?

00:23:48.160 --> 00:23:52.530
Do we have nothing to
fear but fear itself?

00:23:52.530 --> 00:23:55.060
I am... I am scared
to death of dogs.

00:23:55.060 --> 00:23:56.660
"I mean, dogs are scary things."

00:23:56.660 --> 00:23:59.730
"Theyre... theyre these sort of
strange, failed human beings"

00:23:59.730 --> 00:24:01.460
"who have all these emotions,"

00:24:01.460 --> 00:24:04.000
and yet they have these enormous
teeth at the same time.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.000
I always have that
weird sensation

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:11.300
when Im out on a balcony
or in a high place

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:14.730
"that... where the
bottom is accessible,"

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:17.100
that Im going to climb
over the railing.

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:18.730
That doesnt mean youre going to

00:24:18.730 --> 00:24:20.500
"or youre even
contemplating it,"

00:24:20.500 --> 00:24:22.600
but the fact that
youre in a situation

00:24:22.600 --> 00:24:26.930
"where its possible, it
completely unnerves me."

00:24:26.930 --> 00:24:28.530
Does anyone else have that?

00:24:28.530 --> 00:24:30.530
(laughs) Yeah.

00:24:30.530 --> 00:24:32.560
I think our bodies are
beautifully equipped.

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:36.130
Our reptilian brains and
our animal tendencies

00:24:36.130 --> 00:24:39.800
are generous and
smart and helpful.

00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:42.230
"And you know, if
my house is shaking"

00:24:42.230 --> 00:24:43.500
"in the middle of
an earthquake,"

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:46.800
"I-I hope my body will
kick into high adrenaline,"

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:49.660
grab my dogs and my turtle and
grab everything and leave.

00:24:49.660 --> 00:24:57.730
(rumbling)

00:24:57.730 --> 00:25:02.000
RANDOLPH NESSE: There
are certain situations
that have recurred

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:06.430
over evolutionary time over and
over again that cause fear.

00:25:06.430 --> 00:25:10.660
"For instance, some nasty animal
running toward you very fast"

00:25:10.660 --> 00:25:12.300
and baring its fangs.

00:25:12.300 --> 00:25:15.000
"Thats the kind of situation
thats happened not too often,"

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:16.800
but often enough
so that individuals

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:19.100
who have what we call a
fight-flight response

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:20.530
have a lot of advantages

00:25:20.530 --> 00:25:23.300
"over those who say,
""Oh, hello, kitty."""

00:25:23.300 --> 00:25:26.160
"Uh, its just not a good
thing to be, you know,"

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:27.530
laid-back and mellow

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:30.700
when theres a lion coming
towards you very quickly.

00:25:30.700 --> 00:25:33.800
"So, in the clinic, of course,
we call this a panic attack."

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:35.730
A panic attack is just identical

00:25:35.730 --> 00:25:37.200
"to a fight-flight response,"

00:25:37.200 --> 00:25:39.530
"and its perfectly
normal lots of the time,"

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:42.000
but not usually in
a grocery store.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:43.630
GILBERT: Many of the fears

00:25:43.630 --> 00:25:45.630
that weve inherited
from our ancestors

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:48.900
are perfectly rational.

00:25:48.900 --> 00:25:51.100
It makes sense to be wary

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:53.100
"of small spaces
and thunderstorms,"

00:25:53.100 --> 00:25:55.230
"and even snakes,"

00:25:55.230 --> 00:26:00.530
like this fairly large python
thats crawling on me now.

00:26:00.530 --> 00:26:02.530
But sometimes our
fear is irrational.

00:26:02.530 --> 00:26:04.600
"Its more intense
than it ought to be,"

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:06.960
or its in reaction to things
that cant really hurt us.

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:08.960
"These fears are
called phobias,"

00:26:08.960 --> 00:26:11.100
"and for some people,
theyre so debilitating"

00:26:11.100 --> 00:26:13.230
that they need help
overcoming them.

00:26:13.230 --> 00:26:16.760
"In some cases, anti-anxiety
medication can be helpful."

00:26:16.760 --> 00:26:18.900
"If someone flies a
few times a year,"

00:26:18.900 --> 00:26:20.360
and they... and they get anxious

00:26:20.360 --> 00:26:22.060
"every time it
starts to lift off,"

00:26:22.060 --> 00:26:23.860
"or-or typically
when it lands, um,"

00:26:23.860 --> 00:26:26.230
theres nothing wrong with
taking a pill for that.

00:26:26.230 --> 00:26:27.900
"If, on the other
hand, youre somebody"

00:26:27.900 --> 00:26:29.800
"who has to fly
several times a week,"

00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:31.860
"or, you know, a couple
of times a month,"

00:26:31.860 --> 00:26:33.200
"and its part of your life,"

00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:35.030
then that may not be
the best treatment.

00:26:35.030 --> 00:26:39.930
Then what you want to do is to
actually change your behavior.

00:26:39.930 --> 00:26:44.460
GILBERT: Medications havent
worked for Christina Kelley.

00:26:44.460 --> 00:26:47.430
"With emotions, its often
a paradox, you know?"

00:26:47.430 --> 00:26:49.630
"That the more we dont
want an emotional state,"

00:26:49.630 --> 00:26:51.100
the more that we experience it.

00:26:51.100 --> 00:26:53.530
"Right? And as soon as we
allow the emotion to come,"

00:26:53.530 --> 00:26:56.200
"a lot of times,
it kind of starts to
diminish more quickly."

00:26:56.200 --> 00:26:59.700
"GILBERT: Today,
Christina Kelley will
attempt to board a plane"

00:26:59.700 --> 00:27:01.630
"with Todd Farchione,"

00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:04.160
the therapist who is helping
her conquer the phobia

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:06.460
thats kept her from traveling
to visit friends and family.

00:27:06.460 --> 00:27:07.760
Just the way it is.

00:27:07.760 --> 00:27:09.630
"Whether you feel things,
or you dont feel things,"

00:27:09.630 --> 00:27:10.900
"whether its bumpy,"

00:27:10.900 --> 00:27:12.960
"or not bumpy, that you can
handle that situation."

00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:14.560
Thats the most important thing.

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:17.300
"GILBERT: Dr. Farchione uses
cognitive behavioral therapy,"

00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:20.830
"or CBT, which is
extremely effective"

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:23.000
for people with
specific phobias.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:29.100
About 85% of those who try it
show significant improvement.

00:27:29.100 --> 00:27:32.300
"FRIEDMAN: Cognitive
behavioral therapy has
got a different focus,"

00:27:32.300 --> 00:27:34.130
which is on identifying

00:27:34.130 --> 00:27:37.060
and correcting dysfunctional
thoughts and feelings

00:27:37.060 --> 00:27:38.930
that make you miserable.

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:42.060
"So, a cognitive behavior
therapist is not so interested"

00:27:42.060 --> 00:27:44.500
in why you have those
thoughts or feelings.

00:27:44.500 --> 00:27:46.500
"Hes interested, or
shes interested,"

00:27:46.500 --> 00:27:48.400
in basically getting
you to identify them

00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:49.800
and challenge them.

00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:52.060
We say you have a little machine

00:27:52.060 --> 00:27:55.230
"down, buried in your
emotional brain."

00:27:55.230 --> 00:27:58.460
"And its spitting
out, you know,"

00:27:58.460 --> 00:28:01.960
all of these really
scary kinds of thoughts.

00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:05.500
"But because youre the one
thinking those thoughts,"

00:28:05.500 --> 00:28:07.300
you tend to believe it.

00:28:07.300 --> 00:28:10.930
So we have a saying
in cognitive therapy--

00:28:10.930 --> 00:28:13.100
"""Dont believe
everything you think."""

00:28:13.100 --> 00:28:16.260
"GILBERT: Christinas therapy
started two days earlier,"

00:28:16.260 --> 00:28:19.800
when she met Dr.
Farchione at his office.

00:28:19.800 --> 00:28:22.660
Most people sign up for a
dozen or more treatments

00:28:22.660 --> 00:28:24.260
"over a period of weeks,"

00:28:24.260 --> 00:28:27.130
but Christina opted
for a marathon session

00:28:27.130 --> 00:28:29.260
lasting three days.

00:28:29.260 --> 00:28:31.300
"Well, let me just start"

00:28:31.300 --> 00:28:34.230
"by asking you how you, uh,
how you did last night."

00:28:34.230 --> 00:28:36.030
Good. Um...

00:28:36.030 --> 00:28:38.630
I tried to explain
it all to my family.

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:40.000
Right.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.500
"So I think that helps me
kind of, like, go over it."

00:28:42.500 --> 00:28:43.730
"So at this point,"

00:28:43.730 --> 00:28:45.360
how are you feeling
about taking that flight?

00:28:45.360 --> 00:28:46.700
Im very nervous.

00:28:46.700 --> 00:28:50.200
"And, uh, it-it-it switches
back and forth between,"

00:28:50.200 --> 00:28:53.760
"like, I can do this, and
then, suddenly, Ill feel like"

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:56.000
"this is really overwhelming,
and, like, all at once,"

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.360
and I cant believe
Im doing this. Um...

00:28:58.360 --> 00:28:59.660
"With panic,"

00:28:59.660 --> 00:29:02.460
what often happens is that
it becomes this cycle.

00:29:02.460 --> 00:29:05.730
"Um, that theres a recognition
of the physical symptoms,"

00:29:05.730 --> 00:29:08.560
"and as a result of that,
theres then an increase"

00:29:08.560 --> 00:29:10.900
"in the actual physical
response, right?"

00:29:10.900 --> 00:29:13.000
"An increase in those
symptoms, right?"

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:15.360
"So as you are approaching
the plane, for instance,"

00:29:15.360 --> 00:29:17.260
"if you start having
physical feelings,"

00:29:17.260 --> 00:29:19.330
"and you say to yourself, like,
""Well, theyre not going"

00:29:19.330 --> 00:29:21.600
"to go away,"" or ""This is
going to be really bad;"

00:29:21.600 --> 00:29:23.430
"this is going to
be an awful trip,"""

00:29:23.430 --> 00:29:25.500
"this type of thing,
um, its likely"

00:29:25.500 --> 00:29:28.000
that that... physiological
changes are going

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:29.460
"to increase, right?"

00:29:29.460 --> 00:29:32.660
"So one of the things that we
want to do is, we want to see"

00:29:32.660 --> 00:29:34.330
"if we cant elicit some
of these symptoms,"

00:29:34.330 --> 00:29:36.030
"um, in part so
that you can see"

00:29:36.030 --> 00:29:38.260
that this is just your body
doing what your body should do.

00:29:38.260 --> 00:29:40.130
"GILBERT: Early in the session,"

00:29:40.130 --> 00:29:44.100
Dr. Farchione asked Christina
to do a series of exercises

00:29:44.100 --> 00:29:46.730
that bring about some of
the physical sensations

00:29:46.730 --> 00:29:47.930
"associated with fear,"

00:29:47.930 --> 00:29:50.560
such as dizziness...

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:52.900
shortness of breath...

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:56.630
and a racing heart.

00:29:56.630 --> 00:29:58.030
(exhales)

00:29:58.030 --> 00:30:00.400
The idea is that once Christina
becomes more familiar

00:30:00.400 --> 00:30:01.830
"with these sensations,"

00:30:01.830 --> 00:30:03.660
she will become
less afraid of them.

00:30:03.660 --> 00:30:05.230
And how similar is that

00:30:05.230 --> 00:30:07.360
to what you experience
prior to flying?

00:30:07.360 --> 00:30:08.560
"Uh, pretty similar."

00:30:08.560 --> 00:30:10.130
"Like, a six or a seven."

00:30:10.130 --> 00:30:11.760
"Okay, a six or a seven."

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:14.930
"Were going to go into
this, um... this flight"

00:30:14.930 --> 00:30:16.800
"with no safeties,
no avoidance,"

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:18.530
"and essentially,"

00:30:18.530 --> 00:30:20.660
confront what it is
that youre afraid of.

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:22.900
And if that means
experiencing those sensations

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:25.000
"in that situation, again,
thats not a problem."

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.530
"Then its a matter of
allowing them to come,"

00:30:27.530 --> 00:30:31.160
and allowing them to
diminish of their own accord.

00:30:31.160 --> 00:30:32.630
"You know, if somethings
terrorizing you,"

00:30:32.630 --> 00:30:35.060
"terrorizing you
and bothering you,"

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:37.160
"like, lets not...
lets not run away."

00:30:37.160 --> 00:30:39.230
"Lets go find it, you know?"

00:30:39.230 --> 00:30:51.100
(crying)

00:30:51.100 --> 00:30:57.300
(sniffles)

00:30:57.300 --> 00:31:02.660
(sniffles) This is overwhelming.

00:31:02.660 --> 00:31:05.860
"Um, if you had to rate it on
a zero-to-eight-point scale,"

00:31:05.860 --> 00:31:09.030
where would you put your
anticipatory distress right now?

00:31:09.030 --> 00:31:10.200
Eight.

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:11.430
Eight. Okay.

00:31:11.430 --> 00:31:13.160
So its pretty...
its pretty high.

00:31:13.160 --> 00:31:15.130
GILBERT: Dr. Farchione
encouraged Christina

00:31:15.130 --> 00:31:17.330
"not to push the frightening
thoughts aside,"

00:31:17.330 --> 00:31:20.060
"but instead, to let
them come to mind"

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:24.360
so that they can be
examined or reappraised.

00:31:24.360 --> 00:31:28.000
"So, what can we come up with
as a good alternative here?"

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:30.560
"Its going to be hard,
but its going to be okay."

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:32.030
Okay.

00:31:32.030 --> 00:31:33.260
So wait a minute.

00:31:33.260 --> 00:31:34.660
Its going to be hard.

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:36.730
Im going to feel...?

00:31:36.730 --> 00:31:38.200
Scared and panicky.

00:31:38.200 --> 00:31:39.660
Yup? Good.

00:31:39.660 --> 00:31:42.760
GILBERT: One of the key
principles behind CBT

00:31:42.760 --> 00:31:44.760
is that we can
change our feelings

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:47.360
by changing the thoughts
that produce them.

00:31:47.360 --> 00:31:50.500
BARLOW: Were not trying to
stamp out all bad thoughts.

00:31:50.500 --> 00:31:52.900
"In fact, that might
be counterproductive."

00:31:52.900 --> 00:31:55.800
"Were just trying to say, ""Lets
look at the alternative."

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:57.500
"""Lets put this
in perspective."

00:31:57.500 --> 00:31:59.860
"Lets reappraise this."""

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:02.460
"And, oh, yeah, youll continue
to have scary thoughts."

00:32:02.460 --> 00:32:03.860
But you know what?

00:32:03.860 --> 00:32:05.460
You can live with them.

00:32:05.460 --> 00:32:07.800
"And when they do that,"

00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:10.030
it actually changes
brain function.

00:32:10.030 --> 00:32:13.360
"There are changes in
the prefrontal cortex,"

00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:15.200
"working down into
the emotional brain,"

00:32:15.200 --> 00:32:19.200
just by this really working
hard on reappraising.

00:32:19.200 --> 00:32:21.160
Allowing it to unfold
is actually going to be

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:24.130
"the fastest way for it to...
for it to diminish, all right?"

00:32:24.130 --> 00:32:25.530
Yeah. But youre still...

00:32:25.530 --> 00:32:28.030
"youre still scared, and
you still need to do this."

00:32:28.030 --> 00:32:29.200
Okay. Okay.

00:32:29.200 --> 00:32:30.600
"All right, Todd,"

00:32:30.600 --> 00:32:33.100
your return boarding pass is
stapled right on the back.

00:32:33.100 --> 00:32:35.160
GILBERT: Now comes
the decisive moment.

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:38.260
Christina will attempt
to board a plane.

00:32:38.260 --> 00:32:41.760
Cognitive behavioral
therapy has a cognitive

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:43.300
"or thinking component,"

00:32:43.300 --> 00:32:45.560
but it also has a
behavioral component.

00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:48.730
We must go out and do
the things were afraid of

00:32:48.730 --> 00:32:50.600
so that we can learn
from experience

00:32:50.600 --> 00:32:52.400
not to be afraid of them.

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:55.730
BARLOW: The important
thing is that reappraisal--

00:32:55.730 --> 00:32:59.630
it has to be paired with
what we call exposure.

00:32:59.630 --> 00:33:01.000
Ticket. Ah.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:04.900
BARLOW: Where people will
begin to put themselves

00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:06.800
in the feared situation--

00:33:06.800 --> 00:33:09.330
"under therapeutic guidance,"

00:33:09.330 --> 00:33:11.860
and with the appropriate
coping mechanisms--

00:33:11.860 --> 00:33:14.260
where their emotional brain

00:33:14.260 --> 00:33:17.400
can really begin to learn
and become convinced

00:33:17.400 --> 00:33:19.360
that these terrible things

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:21.430
will not happen.

00:33:21.430 --> 00:33:24.160
Whats wrong with the way that
youre feeling right now?

00:33:24.160 --> 00:33:25.730
It sucks.

00:33:25.730 --> 00:33:27.130
What sucks about it?

00:33:27.130 --> 00:33:29.130
Its not comfortable.

00:33:29.130 --> 00:33:31.360
Whats the most
uncomfortable part of it?

00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:33.060
Is it the heart?

00:33:33.060 --> 00:33:34.930
The heart rate?

00:33:34.930 --> 00:33:37.730
Its feeling like
Im going to cry.

00:33:37.730 --> 00:33:40.160
"And have been, for the
last, like, three days."

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:41.600
Thats not fun.

00:33:41.600 --> 00:33:43.160
"Okay, so its-its feeling..."

00:33:43.160 --> 00:33:45.000
its feeling as
though you might cry.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.130
And what... what is the
implications of that?

00:33:47.130 --> 00:33:48.500
What if you did cry?

00:33:48.500 --> 00:33:50.360
I dont want... Im
not going to cry.

00:33:50.360 --> 00:33:52.830
What if you did?

00:33:52.830 --> 00:33:55.500
"Well, that just
makes it worse."

00:33:55.500 --> 00:33:57.200
It does? Yeah.

00:33:57.200 --> 00:34:00.730
WOMAN (over P.A.): Take
a moment to review the
safety information card

00:34:00.730 --> 00:34:02.060
in your seat back pocket.

00:34:02.060 --> 00:34:04.630
Passengers seated in rows
nine and ten are also asked

00:34:04.630 --> 00:34:06.330
to review exit row
seating requirements...

00:34:06.330 --> 00:34:09.060
BARLOW: What were trying
to end up with is somebody

00:34:09.060 --> 00:34:12.360
who can totally
accept the full range

00:34:12.360 --> 00:34:14.960
of their emotional experience--

00:34:14.960 --> 00:34:17.860
"be aware of what their
emotions are doing,"

00:34:17.860 --> 00:34:19.800
"in the way theyre
making you feel,"

00:34:19.800 --> 00:34:21.900
"the way theyre
making you think,"

00:34:21.900 --> 00:34:24.600
"the way theyre
making you behave,"

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:26.400
and accept that.

00:34:26.400 --> 00:34:30.130
"And sort of be with it, and
distance yourself from it."

00:34:30.130 --> 00:34:46.560
"And in so doing, put the
emotion in its place."

00:34:46.560 --> 00:34:49.400
I sort of like this idea
of you moving around

00:34:49.400 --> 00:34:52.360
"a little bit, so if you can..."

00:34:52.360 --> 00:34:53.800
"Like, get up, or just...?"

00:34:53.800 --> 00:34:56.100
"Um, yeah, maybe get up,
maybe see if theres anything"

00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:57.960
"in the overheads, uh,
that you might need."

00:34:57.960 --> 00:35:01.200
"Um, if you want, you can put
my coat up in the overhead,"

00:35:01.200 --> 00:35:02.430
or something along those lines.

